#X text 46 34 There's no limit for the dertuning parameter. By default we have '0' \, which means no detuning \, so all oscillators are on the same frequency! The detuning parameter is in cents \, but it reflects the maximum detuning value up or down.;
#X text 46 83 In the default mode and for an odd number of oscillators \, we have the central oscillator tuned to the input frequency and the outer ones are detuned. The outer oscillators on the extremes are the ones that have the maximum detuning values. For a detuning of 10 cents \, the one to the right is 10 cents higher and the one to the left is 10 cents lower. For an even number of partials \, there's no center oscillator tuned to the input frequency \, so all are detuned.;
#X text 46 176 The default mode take a detuning curve \, which is "1" and evenly spaces the detuning. Like the spread curve \, this parameter affects only 4 or more oscillators. The curve values goes from 0.1 to 10 and closer to 0.1 makes the in between oscillators more closely to outer extremes \, whereas values near 10 make them closer to the center oscillator., f 60;
#X msg 100 370 detcurve \$1;
#X obj 100 406 else/superosc~ -square 110, f 27;
